The cradle of the dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: the two-metre-long and 1.50 meter-tall animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickloops and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would not be special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, say Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in the journal Science on Thursday.
The animal lived in what is now New Mexico about 215 million years ago, which was located in a dry zone of the pangäa supercontinent on the equator.
Tawa opens a new window to the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
He shows us a lot about the relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other palaeontologists began an excavation at the Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
We have sometimes found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unprecedented for deposits from the Triassic, reports team member Randall Irmis from the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Some of the bones quickly identified the researchers as a new species.
During the excavation, they brought together the remains of a total of five individuals.
Fund confirms theories about Dino early history
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it is an extraordinary find: "Dinosaurulent fossils from the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not necessarily share the enthusiasm.
This find is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to the current doctrine, the dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, which is why the assignment of these original dooms is mostly controversial.
For example, the experts debate when the lizards split into their three most important lines of development: the carnivorous theropods, which later included the Tyrannosaurus rex, the Velociraptor and the birds, who known as "Langhälse" and their relatives, and the plant-eating ornithischia trees, for example, and the species.
After the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa is a primitive Theropode.
He has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced qualities, says Nesbitt.
At the skull of Tawa hallae, for example, the researchers found evidence of air sacs, such as the descendants of the theropods, the birds, possess.
Thanks to the air sacs, the breathing of the birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
At Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive Theropode with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Since the related line of the huge sauropods later also had air sacs and lightweight bones, the common ancestor of both groups had probably already produced this useful innovation.
At least three migration waves to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known so far lived in South America, the researchers conclude that the lizards were showing up there for the first time.
Accordingly, the three lines of development separated early on and spread from South America across all parts of the world, which at that time formed a single land mass as a supercontinent Pangäa.
This is said by the fact that the team, together with Tawa, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods.
The three cannot be descended from a common, immigrant ancestry, the researchers argue.
We believe that there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner from the American Museum of Natural History in New York, a co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in today's Poland, says the paleontologist in Bonn, Martin Sander.
His opinion could result in a distorted picture, because in South America a lot of primitive dino fossils have been preserved, while there is hardly anything to be found on other continents.
How the dinosaurs managed to develop from a relatively rare lateral line of the reptile trunk to the dominant land vertebrate of the Middle Ages is still puzzling.
During the Trias, the dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and the flight dinosaurs and with numerous other lizards.
Towards the end of the Triassic, the dinosaurs spread around the world and developed many new species, while the kinship died out on the border from the Triassic to the Jura.
Success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted so that they could beat the competition out of the field.
The success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped a group of animals to flower, which had also developed in the Triassic and since then had a shadow existence: the mammals.
Solidarity from Vienna to Sao Paulo
