Support for braking manoeuvres in critical situations is now mandatory
As with the ABS anti-lock braking system and as is now happening with the ESP stability control, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergencies must become a mandatory equipment in European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly registered passenger cars and light vans, and a waiting period for the remaining vehicles was set by the end of February 2011.
The decision taken by the European Union is aimed at improving the protection of pavers, but these braking systems can also help to prevent many rear-end collisions due to their way of working.
The task of the emergency brake assist is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking manoeuvre, which the system detects on the brake pedal based on the brake strength executed by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to an investigation commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, a third of the drivers involved in an accident did not even come to step on the brake pedal before the collision, and half of them had not slowed down with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The braking aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the braking system and thus reduces the braking time and thus also the braking distance that a car travels during the braking process.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents every year could be prevented if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - one expects that one in four companies could be prevented by personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
The vehicle is then equipped with a system that detects obstacles (via radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time exerting a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, the system will help him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not react to the warning and even if the collision is already inevitable, the brake assist exerts the maximum pressure on the brakes, in order to keep the damage as low as possible.
