New programs for the evaluation of vehicles
In these days of storms and accidents not only earn the car workshops
Every day, thousands of vehicles involved in an accident are towed into the workshops, where an expert has to assess the damage and costs for the repair.
Not a single accident is the same and the calculation of costs for the parts and working hours can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of the repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros by hand, including the parts and working hours, can take up to two or three hours.
In contrast, with the support of the latest computer tooling, it is a matter of minutes
That is why almost 100% of the experts use this type of systems.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repair collect the information they receive from the manufacturers in order to then process them and offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the American group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all reports are prepared with their products.
The other two companies that compete with the tool market for review and drafting a report are GtMots and Eurotax.
Working with the data provided by the manufacturers is anything but easy.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, Audatex Sales Manager, each of them is collaborated with 63 manufacturers and importers, with each of them providing the information in a different format.
Furthermore, the amount of data to be processed becomes ever greater, to the point that even more versions, variants and motorisations have been brought to the market in the last five years than in the entire fifteen years before.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for companies.
It is a tedious task, because every single of the thousand parts of the vehicle has to be entered catalytic and its price.
In addition, each model creates an "intelligent" graphic image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure proceeds quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. Audatex currently has complete information with 99.2% of cars sold in Spain.
Among the more exclusive models, for example, they have information about the Porsche models, but not Ferrari or Lamborghini.
In terms of the vehicle fleet moving on the route, it is over 99%.
In order to carry out the documentation work and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centers distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan), and each of them specializes in specific brands.
The national headquarters are located in Alcobendas, Madrid.
More than a hundred technicians (usually mechanical experts) work there simultaneously with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros annually in the development of these databases.
Every month, they absorb 2.5 million data and their customers receive updates every other day.
The development of this enormous flow of information allows companies to use them in different ways and thereby offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, however, depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or calculating the filing or residual value of a car.
